comment_text: I really like your videos, but this one was surprisingly having some issues I would not expect from you. Especially in the AI segment. First the Google Voice search is not the Assistant. It is basically a Google Search with voice feature. It is not the most elegant solution to me, but a different usecase. But then, instead of just instantly talking to Gemini for the Voice Input you start Gemini Live, which is a very lightweight instantly answering no connection to anything service. It is "just a fancy tech demo of how to talk in real time". Gemini itself is capable of doing all these things you asked for. By either using Gemini's normal voice input, or typing the request. There it also uses a cloud based image generated, while the one in Pixel Studio is a very lightweight on the phone-ish one. Mistakes can happen, but combined with blaming lazy app ports and some other aspects it feels weirdly "I did not like the phone and need some reasons to list" like than the usually pretty informed way. The phone has flaws and should be criticized for them. But mentioning these things as weaknesses with their own segments is just feeling off.

comment_text:
Considering the lack of a lot of the bells and whistles other flagships have including superior performance, this phone should've maintained the older pricing model to be competitive.

As a long time Pixel user, I need the Pixel 10 and onwards to solve the following:
1. Integrate Gemini and G Assistant into a seamless phone assistant that is smart in knowing when to use what. Also should work without wifi for simple tasks like setting alarms, searching files on phone, etc.
2. Get more Pixel specific features that don't come on other phones before the Pixel and also are not gimmicks like A LOT of the AI features introduced recently. Need more useful ones like Hold for Me, Screen Call, Add Me, etc.
3. Give more customization for power users/people who just want to customize.
    a. Give users the option to use a UI that actually takes advantage of the screen real-estate instead of using UI elements that take up half the page just to turn on/off airplane mode.
    b. Give users the option to revert the quick settings menu in the notification shade to actually work like actual toggles again instead of buttons that open mini-windows. Literally every other OS has this figured out including iOS. Why Google changed the behavior is beyond me.
    c. Not really a Pixel issue but Google Keep needs better features and needs more robust note-taking capabilities.
    d. Way better customization is needed akin to GoodLock on Samsung. 3rd party launchers make the phone sluggish and also ruin the seamless look of the phone.
    e. Just general customization that you would find on any 3rd party launchers. 
4. Fix the issues in the camera. 
    a. Video is still behind in Android phones in general vs iPhones. Google should take the big steps to finally improve this and lead.
    b. Fix the stuttery zoom in/out.
    c. Add higher zoom ranges for Pro models.
    d. 3rd party apps should have the same camera quality as using the camera app. This is for all Android phones. Google should whip these app devs to force them to finally get it right.
5. Flagship pricing = flagship features. That means at least 45W+ fast charging, Qi 2, SiC batteries, flagship processor, better codec support, UFS 4.0, Gorilla Armor 2, etc.
6. Treats. Add cool features that aren't a need but a nice to have like a stylus(like the galaxy ultra).

A personal one that I want Google to do is abandon glossy glass back & glossy metal siderails. Always use satin/matte back and siderails. Glossy is disgusting. Samsung has it figured out.

comment_text: My only complaint about my 9 Pro XL is that the corners are just too round. It cuts off part kf6 the screen that often has information there. Also, the corners aren't touch sensitive in spite of being able to see things. For example, if I'm trying to send a message in FB messenger but the keyboard is hidden so the send button is way down at the bottom left of the screen, it's hard to find just the right spot to hit the send button in spite of being able to see it. As for the rest of the features talked about, during every day usage, it's still pretty good. But Gemini definitely needs some work. It is neat to have a conversation with it like you'd talk to a person but overall it's just not that useful yet. The processor is a little lackluster but it works well and even does a great job playing games in spite of not being quite as fast as the snapdragon chips. But my 2 favorite things about this phone are the camera and the stock android experience. Great photots and it doesn't have tons of bloat ware on it, which was my main reason for switching from Samsung. All the bloat ware was awful. So I'm like 90% happy with my Pixel phone and would recommend them.
